en","about 1370":"circa 1370","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1392":"1392","1447":"1447","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1333":"1333","1375":"1375","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Haigh, Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, Greater Manchester, England":"Haigh, Greater Manchester, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barnsley, Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley, South Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Seginworth, , Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Southange, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1350–1388":"1350–1388","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1373–1424":"1373–1424","1375–1447":"1375–1447","1381–1445":"1381–1445","1333–Female":"1333–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1392":"1392","1447":"1447","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1333":"1333","1375":"1375","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Haigh, Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, Greater Manchester, England":"Haigh, Greater Manchester, England, United Kingdom","Barnsley, Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley, South Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Seginworth, , Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Southange, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bailiffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, from Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baillif</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>bailli(s)</i>, <i>baillif</i>). The term could denote the king's officer in a county, hundred, town, castle, or forest, or an elected town officer, a magistrate, an officer of a court, serving warrants and enforcing judgments. In Middle English, a bailiff often denoted the agent of a lord in managing a manor, collecting rents, etc., but in the early modern period the term gradually because specialized as denoting an officer of justice under a sheriff, who executes writs and processes, distraints, and arrests. Compare the variant   Bayliff  ,   Bayliss   and also   Bailey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bayliff","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  . See also   Bayliss  ."]},{"name":"Bayliss","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, an occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, whose duties included serving writs, distraining goods, and (formerly) arresting people. In England it was formerly a status name for the chief officer of a hundred (administrative subdivision of a county). The derivation is from Middle English, Old French <i>bailis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i> (adjective), ‘pertaining to an attendant or porter’ (see   Bailey  ).","History: Thomas Baylies, a prominent Quaker, came to Boston from London in 1737."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Jane Bailiffe was born in 1345, in Barnsley, Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Mrs. Roger Bailiffe. She married William Wiatt de Southange about 1370, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1392, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1350–1388":"1350–1388","1372–1440":"1372–1440","1373–1424":"1373–1424","1375–1447":"1375–1447","1381–1445":"1381–1445","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1392":"1392","1447":"1447","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","1333":"1333","1375":"1375","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Haigh, Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, Greater Manchester, England":"Haigh, Greater Manchester, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barnsley, Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley, South Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Seginworth, , Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Southange, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi